title: girls'_frontline_glitch_land
body:
A fan game-turned-official announced during MICA Team's 4th Anniversary Stream, May 15, 2020. A top-down side scrolling pixel-based adventure game set to star [[HK416 (girls' frontline)|]] as the main protagonist, set before the beginning of the core [[Girls' Frontline]] story. Other characters that were slated to appear, aside those original to it (i.e. Anna, a SF researcher, and unnamed characters from its teaser), included [[Thunder (girls' frontline)|]] (wearing a labcoat) and [[M870 (girls' frontline)|]].

Was announced to be "shelved":https://www.reddit.com/r/girlsfrontline/comments/spz4e3/news_on_gfl_glitchland/ on February 11, 2021, a victim of increasing regulations on game registration in China (including the suspension of the approval of newly registered gaming IPs) preventing the game's release, with the original creator leaving Sunborn amicably and speaking favorably of his time there.

title: cuffs
body:
A band typically of leather and/or metal that fits around the wrist, arms, legs, or ankles of a person.  These bands are typically used to restrain the wearer by linking the cuffs together by chains or metal rods, or by linking the cuffs to a wall or object.  Highly associated with [[bondage]].

For distinctive fabric cuffs at the end of sleeves, use [[sleeve cuffs]]. For decorative bands or what looks like detached sleeve cuffs worn around the wrist use the [[wrist cuffs]] tag.

The term cuffs is also slang for [[handcuffs]], but for tagging purposes the handcuffs tag should be used only for images depicting the metal handcuffs used by the police.

Cuffs worn around the ankles are also tagged [[ankle cuffs]]. For frilled fabric cuffs worn around the ankles, use [[ankle garter]] instead.

title: animated_png
body:
An animated image in the APNG format, an unofficial, backwards-compatible extension to the PNG format created by the group behind Mozilla/Firefox. Comparable to [[animated gif]] files, but with support for 24-bit colour and 8-bit transparency.

Not fully supported by all browsers. Internet Explorer and EdgeHTML-based Microsoft Edge will only display a preview image, but the animation should display properly in Firefox, Chrome (v. 59 onwards), SeaMonkey, Safari, Opera (prior to v. 15) or Chromium-based Edge. Also note that the animation is not preserved when previewing or resizing the image, so make sure to click on "view original" if you wish to view more than the static preview image. In addition to these browsers, there is also support for the format in a few stand-alone image browsers. 

This tag is automatically added by the site to new uploads.

h4. See also

* [[Tag Group:Image Composition]]

h4. External links

* "Chrome Web Store: APNG for Chrome":https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/apng/ehkepjiconegkhpodgoaeamnpckdbblp (an extension for viewing APNGs in Chrome prior to v. 59)

An image that has been [[third-party edit|edited]] by a third party to replace the original text (Japanese or otherwise) with a translation into English (or [[hard-translated (non-english)|another language]]).

This regularly occurs in [[comic|comics]] and [[doujinshi]], [[scan|scanlated]] or otherwise.

Uploading hard-translated images is discouraged, due to image quality issues, typographical issues, and the difficulty of confirming the correctness of the translations (see topic #2590 for discussion). The original image should be uploaded instead, and the translations applied via [[help:notes|notes]]. Non-original hard translations [[help:post relationships|should be made children]] of the original images whenever the latter can be found.

Posts that are hard-translated by the artist themselves should be tagged [[alternate language]] instead.

body:
バイド ([b]BYDO[/b]) is a recurring antagonist force in the [[R-Type]] series.

At first, nothing was known about the enemies known as the Bydo Empire other than their name. In [[R-TYPE III]], it was established that the Bydo were "the disastrous results of a gigantic composite biological weapon gone rogue, created by humankind in the 26th century".  (It is now the 22nd century.) However, because they are united under the entity known as the Bydo Core, the term "Bydo Empire" continues to be used out of convenience.

This life-form has a multitude of different forms, due to their ability to convert any type of matter, living or not, into their own. Naturally, the craft the player pilots is no exception.
Sentient beings that have been transformed into Bydo are often unaware of the changes in their own bodies. This tragic plot is one of the most popular elements of the game series.

title: namco
body:
A Japanese corporation best known as a former [[video game]] developer and publisher. Following a merger with [[Bandai]] in September 2005, the two companies' game production assets were spun off into [[Bandai Namco|Bandai Namco Games]] on March 31, 2006. Namco was re-established to continue domestic operation of video arcades and amusement parks. Its headquarters are located in Oota, Tokyo. The company's English name is officially often written as [b]NAMCO[/b] (in all capital letters).

Namco was a front-runner during the Golden age of [[arcade]] video games. [[Pac-Man]], its arguably most famous title, went on to become the best-selling arcade game in history and an international popular culture icon. They went on to create other hit franchises such as [[Splatterhouse]], [[Steel Gunner]], [[Tekken]], [[SoulCalibur]], [[Ridge Racer]], and [[Ace Combat]].

title: solar_eclipse
body:
An astronomical event where the moon passes between the sun and the earth, and the moon partially or completely covers the sun as viewed from a location on earth. This can only happen during a new moon, when the sun and moon are in conjunction as seen from earth.

A solar eclipse can be one of two major kinds: a partial eclipse, where the moon partially blocks out the sun; and a total eclipse, where the moon blocks out the sun completely and the sun's light creates a spectacular white ring around the moon.

Solar eclipses are frequently used in fiction to mark important, and often catastrophic, events in the plot.

title: hmas_stuart_(d00/i00)
body:
HMAS Stuart (Pennant Number: D00, later changed to I00) was a Scott class destroyer leader built between 1917-1919.
Served with the Royal Navy Mediterranean station until 1933 where she was transferred to the Royal Australian Navy where she served until being decommissioned and scrapped 1947 in Sydney.
She served as a Flotilla leader, with Captain 'Hec' Waller (killed later during the Battle of Sunda Strait, commanding HMAS Perth, 1942) commanding, for HMA Ships Vampire, Vendetta, Voyager and Waterhen.

Notable to have never taken a hit and never suffered a combat casualty her entire career despite being in multiple close range melees with enemy ships of larger class, most notably during the night following the Battle of Cape Matapan, going against Italian cruisers at point blank.
Also of note is that she spent more than half her combined service life in the Mediterranean in both the Royal Navy and Royal Australian Navy.

After returning from the Mediterranean, she was made a stores / fast transport vessel, being deemed 'too old' for a frontline destroyer, and spent the remainder of her life transporting supplies in and around the Papua New Guinea region until 1946. 



h4.See also

title: pauldrons
body:
A form of [[shoulder armor]], usually made from metal. They often protect the armpit as well as the back and chest, either separately or as part of a large breastplate.

A closely related form of armor is spaulders, which are made of smaller overlapping plates that cover just the shoulder and top of the forearm. Due to continuous misuse of the former "spaulders" tag, on Danbooru, spaulders are now tagged as pauldrons.

title: adeleine
body:
Adeleine is a friend of [[Kirby]] and an artist who is best known for her ability to bring her creations to life.

Much like [[paint_roller_(kirby)|Paint Roller]] back from [i][[Kirby's Adventure]][/i], she can use paintings for combat, most notably in her boss fights. Unlike Paint Roller, she can only be attacked after she runs out from her easel (though she goes down in one hit).

While she's better known for her appearance in [i][[Kirby 64]][/i], she's implied to make her debut earlier in [i][[Kirby's Dream Land 3]][/i] under similar circumstances and a different name ("[[Ado (kirby)|]]", due to name space constraints). Due to differences in design between the two games, some fans like to distinguish the two appearances despite them possibly being the same character, calling the [i]Dream Land 3[/i] design "Ado" and the [i]64[/i] design  "Adeleine". In some cases, the two designs are drawn as twins.

She also appears in [i][[Kirby: Star Allies]][/i] as a Dream Friend with [[ribbon_(kirby)|Ribbon]] by her side. She is part of the second wave of post-launch Dream Friends alongside [[Daroach]] and [[Dark Meta Knight]].

title: talim
body:
Talim is a character from the [[Soulcalibur]] series. She made her debut in [[Soulcalibur II]].

The Last Priestess of the Winds, from the Village of the Wind Deity, she uses a pair of elbow blades called Syi Salika & Loka Luha for her agile fighting style.

She is the first fighting game character who originated from the Philippines, followed by [[Josie Rizal]] in Tekken 7, also made by Namco.

Her name means "sharp" (as an adjective) or "blade" in Tagalog, the officially spoken Filipino dialect.

title: circle_cut
body:
For danbooru purposes a [b]circle cut[/b] (サークルカット) is a special type of advertisement for a doujin circle. There are two basic types pictures tagged as circle cut. The traditional variety has some distinct features:

* There is always a white box with a black border in the upper left corner.
* The circle name is displayed prominently on the cut, as well as textual information about what the circle intends to offer.
* They are (usually) in some standardized size, as specified by the event.
* They are [[monochrome]] for the printed event catalog, however the circle cuts are usually in color for web catalogs.

The box is there for specific information, such as when the doujin circle will be attending an event and where their stand exactly is. The box is also used by event goers as a checkbox, often with a highlighter.

The second kind of picture doesn't need to conform to the visual template exactly, but is characterized by having been released as a direct preparation of the exposition in question. They might vary in appearance from just a character's portrait + circle name, up to entire small scenes or comics whose purpose is to announce the booth number. For example, see post #634255 and post #161515.

Philippe, also known as [b]Wax Artist[/b], is a playable Hunter in [[Identity V]]. He was a talented wax artist and physiognomist with a fervent desire to rid the world of evil-doers before they could even commit crime. His theories and research brought him success, but also earned him the hatred of those who were judged because of him, and it resulted in the death of his beloved sister. Out of grief, Phillipe threw himself into his art and began to create even more lifelike statues, made in the appearance of criminals.
His main ability is to spray wax onto the Survivors and the surrounding environment, limiting the Survivors’ map interaction and stunning or burning them.

Philippe has [[purple skin]] with [[burn scar|burn scars]] over his face and arms, [[long hair|long]] [[black hair]] with [[swept bangs]] and a [[side braid]], [[purple lips]], and [[grey eyes]]. His entire left side is covered in white [[wax]], connected to the wax body of his sister [[Christina (Identity v)|]].
He wears a [[grey shirt|grey]] [[checkered shirt|checkered]] [[collared shirt]] that is [[open shirt|open]] with [[sleeves rolled up]], [[black pants]], [[suspenders]], a [[brown belt]], [[monocle]], [[black socks]] and [[shoes]]. His weapon is a [[hose]] attached with a [[valve]].

title: orpheus_(identity_v)
body:
Orpheus is a character in [[Identity V]] with three identities: the non-playable character "The Detective" and his younger selves - the playable Survivor "The Novelist" and [spoilers]Hunter "[[Nightmare (identity v)|]]" ([i]who isn’t included in this tag[/i])[/spoilers].

As "The Detective", Orpheus is the starting character of the Identity V story introduced in the Tutorial. He was a famous crime novelist, but lost his memory 10 years ago after a fire and became an unsuccessful private detective who then came to the mysterious Oletus Manor on the heels of a missing child case. The story is revealed through Orpheus' ability to deduce the personality and experiences of the characters through their diaries.
Detective Orpheus is a middle-aged man with [[short hair|short]] [[brown hair]] that is [[hair slicked back|combed back]] and [[brown eyes]]. He wears a [[white shirt|white]] [[collared shirt]], [[green vest]], [[red necktie]], [[brown coat|brown]] [[trench coat]], [[black pants]] and [[black footwear|black]] [[shoes]].

"The Novelist" is Orpheus before he lost his memory - a renowned novelist whose past is a mystery to all, even to himself. His main ability is to [[body switch|swap the control of characters]] with either his teammates or the Hunter for a set period of time.
Novelist Orpheus’ physical appearance is similar to Detective Orpheus, except much [[aged down|younger]] and with [[button eyes]] as he is a Survivor. His default outfit includes a [[white shirt|white]] [[collared shirt]], [[green ascot]], [[grey vest]], [[white coat]], [[white pants]], [[black footwear|black]] [[dress shoes]], and a [[monocle]]. He usually holds a [[book]] and a [[nib pen (object)|]].

title: douda_akaruku_nattarou
body:
[i]"Dou da, akaruku nattarou"[/i] ("There, that's brighter, isn't it?") is a dialog caption from a satirical cartoon from about 1928.

While the man in the cartoon is unnamed, he's apparently modeled after "Tadasaburō Yamamoto":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/山本唯三郎, a businessman from humble roots who grew very successful in the late 19th/early 20th century.  He was known for flaunting his enormous wealth.  

One night, Yamamoto was leaving after an extravagant meal at a restaurant in Hakodate, when he saw a geisha searching around in the foyer for her shoes, having trouble because of the darkness.  He therefore pulled out a ¥100 bill (now worth about ¥1 million, allowing for inflation) and lit it to brighten the area.  The incident became famous as an anecdote of [i]nouveau riche[/i] behavior.

Years later, an artist named Kunibo Wada heard of the incident and drew a satirical cartoon depicting the situation, entitled ""The Age of Nouveau Riche Splendor":[https://kyuman.art/themes/main/facility/images/img_works_10.jpg]".  The cartoon appears in current Japanese history textbooks and so has some slight fame among the public.  It had gained a similar level of popularity as a motif for ASCII art and gag images.

title: hange_zoe
body:
A character from [[Shingeki no Kyojin]].

An officer and scientist in the Scouting Legion. Hange is passionate to the extreme about Titans and is driven to study them and learn their secrets. A cheerful and talkative person, they can go on about their experiments on Titans for hours without breaks. They also has a soft spot for their subjects, going as far as crying on their behalf while experimenting on Titan pain resistance.

While Hange Zoë's gender is officially stated to be ambiguous by Hajime Isayama, the anime and live-action adaptations depict them with more feminine features. If Zoë in the post is distinctly female at a glance (e.g. breasts, pronounced hips, feminine clothing), tag as female. Otherwise, tag as "other".

title: karmatron_y_los_transformables
body:
[i][B]Karmatrón y los Transformables[/B][/i] ([I] "Karmatron and the Transformers":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karmatron [/I]) is a Mexican [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] comic book created by [[Oscar Gonzalez Loyo]], and published first by CEPSA in 1986. 

The weekly series was published only in [[Mexico]], non-stop for 5 years, from 1986 to 1991 (until #298). 

The story deals with a group of brave variable geometry [[alien]] robots called the [i]Transformables[/i] (also known as the [i]Stellar Warriors[/i]) who help the powerful titular hero of the series, [i]Karmatron[/i] (a giant super robot), battle evil forces across the universe.

The series is notable because it's considered one of the first Mexican sci-fi [[super robot]] and [[mecha]] "[[comic]]", and because of its once-per-week publication schedule, an uncommon practice at its time of release.

It is fondly remembered by many Mexicans for its unique art style and its diverse and colorful characters, all influenced by American sci-fi and fantasy works (like [[Star Wars]], [[Battlestar Galactica]] and [[Transformers]]) as well as Japanese super robot and mecha anime shows from the 70s and 80s ([[Mazinger Z]] and [[Robotech]]/[[Macross]]). 

According to the creator of the comic many foreign comic artists and authors -who published their works monthly - couldn't believe that a weekly comic was even possible at the time of publication of [i]Karmatron[/i].

The "ancient astronaut theory":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_astronaut_theory is one of the principal components of the main storyline in Karmatron. [[Buddhism]], [[Taoism]], "Esoterism":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_esotericism and "Mayanism":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayanism are also featured heavily in the series.

title: three-nine_(space_train)
body:
The eponymous fictional space craft of the [[Ginga Tetsudou 999]] [[science fiction]] series from the [[1970s_(style)|70s]] created by [[Matsumoto Leiji]].

The [b]Special Limited Express Three-Nine[/b] (銀河超特急 999号) is actually a very advanced and sophisticated long range interstellar transport [[spacecraft]]. It is shaped like an old steam [[train]] so its passengers are more comfortable and feel more at home, becoming less nostalgic of [[earth_(planet)|Earth]] as the ship travels to planets and places located very far away in the far reaches of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy.

It is operated by an [[alien]] called [[Conductor_(ginga_tetsudou_999)|]].

The basic design is based in a [[Japan]]ese National Railways Steam Locomotive "C-62":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JNR_Class_C62] Model.
